The issue is that you are using a ternary operator inside string concatenation in a way that *changes the semantics*. When you do `&quot;start &quot; + bool ? &quot;a&quot; : &quot;b&quot; + &quot; end&quot;` this would be interpreted as `(&quot;start &quot; + bool) ? &quot;a&quot; : (&quot;b&quot; + &quot; end&quot;)`, so you *either* get `&quot;a&quot;` or `&quot;b&quot; + &quot; end&quot;`. The initial expression will always be truthy (string concatenation between a non-empty string and anything else), so you always get the true branch of the ternary.

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    var bool = true;

    var result = &quot;start &quot; + bool ? &quot;a&quot; : &quot;b&quot; + &quot; end&quot;;

    console.log(result);

    bool = false;
    result = &quot;start &quot; + bool ? &quot;a&quot; : &quot;b&quot; + &quot; end&quot;;

    console.log(result);

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

If you *do* use string concatenation and a ternary, you need to group the ternary:

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    var bool = true;

    var result = &quot;start &quot; + (bool ? &quot;a&quot; : &quot;b&quot;) + &quot; end&quot;;

    console.log(result);

    bool = false;
    result = &quot;start &quot; + (bool ? &quot;a&quot; : &quot;b&quot;) + &quot; end&quot;;

    console.log(result);

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

However, since you&#39;re using a template literal, you can just evaluate the expression directly

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    var check = true;

    var html = `&lt;input ${check ? &#39;checked&#39; : &#39; &#39;} type=&quot;checkbox&quot; value=&quot;text&quot; /&gt;`;
    console.log(html)
    document.getElementById(&quot;dv&quot;).innerHTML = html;

&lt;!-- language: lang-html --&gt;

    &lt;div id=&quot;dv&quot;&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

An even better idea is to not generate HTML but create the element programmatically:

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    var check = true;

    var element = document.createElement(&quot;input&quot;);

    element.type = &quot;checkbox&quot;;
    element.value = &quot;text&quot;;
    element.checked = check;

    console.log(element)
    document.getElementById(&quot;dv&quot;).appendChild(element);

&lt;!-- language: lang-html --&gt;

    &lt;div id=&quot;dv&quot;&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

Here is what you need with template literals:

    var check = true;
    
    var html = `&lt;input ${check ? `checked` : ``} type=&quot;checkbox&quot; value=&quot;text&quot; /&gt;`;
    console.log(html)
    document.getElementById(&quot;dv&quot;).innerHTML = html;

